OriginalAxioms:
:LandTransportationVehicle rdfs:comment A specialization of #$LandTransportationDevice and
            #$TransportationDevice-Vehicle.  Each instance of
            #$LandTransportationVehicle is a device which is both
            self-powered and controlled in some fashion by a user, and
            is used for transportation across land. Specializations of
            #$LandTransportationVehicle include the collections
            #$Automobile, #$Snowmobile, #$Truck, and #$Bus-RoadVehicle,
            but not collections of non-#$SelfPoweredDevices such as
            #$Bicycle or #$Skateboard.

:DoublingEvent rdfs:comment A DoublingEvent is an Event in which something increases
          twofold in number, size or  mass, whether by internal causes or externally caused.
          This should be subdivided into transitive Actions and the intransitive increase itself.
          NOTE: if this is an increase in number, it is also a subtype of Multiplying -
            perhaps that should be a subtype of this?
          
          Corresponds to part of verb sense 1 of double in WordNet but doesnt include
          duplicate, and includes noun sense 5 of double in any form of betting:
           WN noun double:
             1. 18 double, duplicate - increase twofold; The population doubled within 50 years
           WN verb double :
            5. doubling, double - raising the stakes in a card game by a factor of 2;
              I decided his double was a bluff

:FixedWingAircraft rdfs:comment A specialization of #$AirTransportationDevice.
            Each instance of #$FixedWingAircraft is an air
            transportation device that has a  fixed wing structure as
            its primary source of lift.  Notable specializations of
            #$FixedWingAircraft include #$Airplane and #$Glider.
            
            NOTE that some aircract such as VSTOL craft, which
            may have wings or motors that rotate to the vertical
            during takeoff and landing, are also categorized
            as FixedWingAircraft because the defining
            characteristic is that the aircraft must derive most
            of its lift during flight from the passage of air
            driven by the forward movement, over some airfoil
            on the craft.

:Barb rdfs:comment A small length of metal wire wrapped into a length of 
           BarbWire, having pointed ends .
          
             Corresponds to noun sense 1 of barb in Wordnet:
                2. barb - the pointed part of barbed wire

:KnownToBeTrue rdfs:comment KnownToBeTrue is the highest level that can be assigned to a document or
      other assertion, and should only be applied to something that has had multiple
      reliable confirmations.
    
      Includes adjective senses 1 of true and 1 and 4 of correct and senses 1 and 5 of right inWordnet:
      WN true:
        1. 84 true - consistent with fact or reality; not false; the story is true;
           it is undesirable to believe a proposition when there is no ground 
           whatever for supposing it true- B. Russell; the true meaning of the statement
        1. 6 correct, right - free from error; especially conforming to fact or truth;
          the correct answer; the correct version; the right answer;
          took the right road; the right decision
        4. right, correct - correct in opinion or judgment; time proved him right

:Joke-IBT rdfs:comment The collection of all #$InformationBearingThings
            whose information content is a #$Joke-CW. A #$Joke-IBT is
            the #$communicationToken in any act of #$JokeTelling.

require five arguments. rdf:type rdf:resource = #InheritableRelation/

:Comfort rdfs:comment Comfort is the Feeling that a person has when
           s/he is relaxed and has no disagreeable sensations.
           NOTE that living in comfort is not included in this sense.
           @ToDo: as of r973, not represented
           
           This represents the state when one is neither positively or
             negatively affected by internal concerns. The subtype Contentment 
             is the feeling achieved when one is positively satisfied by
             gratification of some desires, with few or no offsetting concerns.
             
           This corresponds to sense 1 of comfort in WordNet:
           1. 5 comfort, comfortableness - a state of being relaxed 
             and feeling no pain; he is a man who enjoys his comfort;
             she longed for the comfortableness of her armchair

:GreenColor rdfs:comment The color Green.
        
         Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of green in WordNet:
         1. 26 green, greenish, light-green, dark-green -- of the color between blue and yellow in the color
           spectrum; similar to the color of fresh grass; a green tree; green fields; green paint
         WN noun green:
           1. 6 green, greenness, viridity - green color or pigment; resembling the color of growing grass

         main topic is an Explanation.
         
         NOTE that the WN sense 2 of explain seems to include

           2. 12 explain - define; The committee explained their plan for 
              fund-raising to the Dean

:BiologicalDestructionEvent rdfs:comment A specialization of both
            #$PhysicalDestructionEvent and #$BiologicalProcess.  In each
            instance  of #$BiologicalDestructionEvent, some instances
            of  #$BiologicalLivingObject q.v. are destroyed.  Notable
            specializations of #$BiologicalDestructionEvent include
            #$BiologicalCatabolismEvent, #$DigestionEvent, and #$BiologicalDecompositionEvent.

:LawOfNature rdfs:comment Any physical including chemical and biological 
        law that specifies how things behave when constrained by the
        laws of physics which in turn determine the laws of chemistry
        and biology.  Mystical, supernatural or magical phenomena 
        referenced in discourses may not obey these laws.
        
        For detailed descriptions of Laws of nature, use QuantitativeTendency.
        NOTE that his is not a subtype of Law, which is a term used in
        COSMO only for laws created by governmental authorities.
        
        A quantitative rule Equations that expresses a LawOfNature
        may be related to that LawOfNature by the relation isDescribedByMathematicalRepresentation.
        
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of law of nature in WordNet:
          1. 3 law, law of nature - a generalization that describes recurring facts
             or events in nature; the laws of thermodynamics

:Greece rdfs:comment 
                    RHW: Ancient Greek, Hellas. Modern Greek, Ellas. a republic in S Europe at 
                      the S end of the Balkan Peninsula. 10,583,126; 50,147 sq. mi. 129,880 sq. km. 
                      Cap.: Athens.
:ArtWork rdfs:comment The SUMO equivalent of ArtObject.

      location; in linguistic phrases, the reference location is, usually 
      the location of the speaker.  For the upstairs of a building
      that is above Ground level the upstairs part of a building, use 
      AboveGroundLevel. 
      
      This requires FOL to specify that upstairs is above the
       ReferenceLocation of the assertion.
       
       This includes adverb sense 1 and noun sense 1 of upstairs
         in WordNet:
       WN adverb upstairs:
         1. 13 upstairs, up the stairs, on a higher floor -
           on a floor above; they lived upstairs
       WN noun Upstairs:
         1. upstairs - the part of a building above the ground floor;
           no one was allowed to see the upstairs

:GrowingEvent rdfs:comment An Event in which something increases in size or
          mass due to some action of its own.  Usually what grows is an organism
          or part of an organism, but crystals and mountains can grow. 
          This is considered an Action, though it is not voluntary.  In the case
          of inanimate things like crystals and mountains, attributing agency
          to them is an included borderline use of the notion of GenericAgent.
          
          For growing that is not a physical increase of an Object as in knowledge
            use Development.
          
          An Object produced by a GrowingEvent is a Growth.
          
          Includes noun senses 1 and 3 of growth and verb sense 3 of grow
            in WordNet though WordNet growth seems strictly biological,
            in contrast to the definition of grow:
            WN grow
              3. 34 grow - increase in size by natural process;
                 Corn doesnt grow here; In these forests, mushrooms grow under the trees; 
                 her hair doesnt grow much anymore.
            WN growth:
              1. 37 growth, growing, maturation, development, ontogeny, ontogenesis -
                biology the process of an individual organism growing organically;
                a purely biological unfolding of events involved in an organism
                changing gradually from a simple to a more complex level;
                he proposed an indicator of osseous development in children
              3. 3 increase, increment, growth - a process of becoming larger 
                 or longer or more numerous or more important;
                 the increase in unemployment; the growth of population

:canBeAnAttributeOnlyOf rdfs:comment Points to the type of  Thing that may have this AttributeValue.
              In using this relation, be sure that thething pointed to is the only
              kind of thing that can have this attribute value.
              This is used to clarify the meaning of certain qualitative relations.
               .

:Observation rdfs:comment An Observation is an Assertion concerning something in
      the RealWorld produce by an act of Observing, and that act of Observing
      provides some level of proof for that Assertion.  Assertions about 
      reliable confirmed scientific observations are included, as well
      as Assertions about the properties of things that can be proved 
      from authentic recordings. Its a fact that water melts at 0 degress C.
      
      An Observation may be complex; a single fact one logical sentence is
      represented as a Datum in COSMO.
      
      NOTE that an Observation Action is not itself a VerifiableObservation,
      which is an Assertion about an Observation.
            
      Corresponds approximately to noun sense 4 of fact and non sense
         3 of observation in WordNet;
      4. 27 fact - a concept whose truth can be proved; 
           scientific hypotheses are not facts
      WN noun observation:
      3. 5 observation - facts learned by observing; he reported his observations to the mayor

:LegalSpeedLimit rdfs:comment A LegalSpeedLimit is the maximum speed usually on ground, but
        possibly on water or in the air established by some Law in some
        region e.g. part of a road in some legal jurisdiction.
        
         Includes but is broader than noun sense 1 of speed limit in WordNet:
           1. 3 speed limit - regulation establishing the top speed permitted 
             on a given road

            #$WheeledTransportationDevice, #$MountableTransporter,
            #$Device-UserPowered, and #$Device-UserControlled.  Each
            instance of #$Bicycle is a personal wheeled transport device
            powered by human peddling.   Most bicycles have two main
            wheels arranged in-line, but some tandem bicycles have more
            than two wheels.
            
             Corresponds to noun sense 1 of bicycle in WordNet:
               1. 5 bicycle, bike, wheel, cycle - a wheeled vehicle 
                  that has two wheels and is moved by foot pedals

:isWeightFraction rdfs:comment isWeightFraction is a very specialized relation for subtypes of
    Type FractionalComponentSubstance, which specifies the fraction of
    the domain argument that is represented by the specific instance
    of FractionalComponentSubstance.  In English,
    this might be expressed as 20% Oxygen for a substance whose
    parent is Oxygen, and whose percentage by weight is 20.
    For the rationale requiring this relation, see FractionalComponentSubstance.

:SouthEast rdfs:comment The CompassDirection that is 45 degrees rotated clockwise from
      direct East.
      
       Corresponds to noun sense 1 of southeast in Wordnet:
          1. 1 southeast, sou-east, southeastward, SE - the compass point 
              midway between south and east; at 135 degrees

:AnimalSound rdfs:comment COSMO note: AnimalSounds are interpreted as 
            the Event consisting of the act of an animal emitting the sound.
            plus the Event of the sound wave being propagated.  These subevents
            can be disassociated if necessary.
        
        A specialization of
            #$InformationBearingWavePropagation.  Each instance of
            #$AnimalSound is a sound of a type which originally was, and
            typically is, made by an animal using just its body parts
            though such a sound may subsequently have been reproduced
            by imitation or recording.  Examples of #$AnimalSounds
            include instances of #$Birdsong, #$NeighingSound,
            #$PurringSound, #$BarkingSound, and #$BrayingSound.  Note
            that the restriction to sounds produced by body parts alone
            excludes noises produced by moving external objects;
            consequently, #$AnimalSound does _not_ include rustling the
            leaves underfoot, splashing water, or playing a musical
            instrument. Note that this collection is not a
            specialization of #$Action, or #$BodyMovementEvent, since it
            refers to animal sounds themselves, not to the activity of
            making animal sounds though events of both types usually
            accompany one another. See #$EmittingSound for the latter.

:Poll rdfs:comment A Poll is an Action in which one or more
       Questions are asked of more than one Person, and the
       answers organized to present the Result.
       
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 and verb sense 1 of poll in Wordnet:
           1. 4 poll, opinion poll, public opinion poll, canvass -  an inquiry 
           into public opinion conducted by interviewing a random sample of people
         WN verb poll:

:OutdoorLocation rdfs:comment COSMO note: this is for locations that are in the atomosphere on 
           or near the surface of the Earth, but not inside a structure.   For
           locations on the surface of the Earth that are not inside a structure nor
           in the atmosphere e.g.under water or underground, use OutsideLocation.
        
          CYC: A specialization of #$GeographicalRegion.  Each
            instance of #$OutdoorLocation is a region of outdoor space;
            i.e. a region that is directly subject to atmospheric
            weather.  Thus, the collection #$OutdoorLocation does _not_
            include as instances any instances of #$UnderwaterLocation
            q.v. or any places that are underground see
            #$Underground.  Specializations of #$OutdoorLocation
            include #$MountainRange, #$Stream, and #$Highway.
            
            This is a Location, but it can be a PhyscialObject, so is not disjoint from
               PhysicalObject.
            For the PhysicalObjects that predominantly occupy certain OutdoorLocations
              see subtypes of GeographicalObject.
            
         This is hard to distinguish from outdors in essential
           meaning, though these two words are used in different syntactical
           structures.  @ToDo: perhaps more thought to this?
           
       This sense can also be linguistically signalled by the word out
         Im going out for a walk, but there is no sense of out in WordNet 
         exactly corresponding to this concept - closest is the
         adverb out, only part of which is included in this sense of
         Outdoors:
         WN adverb out
           1. 5 out - away from home; they went out last night.

:Homeotherm rdfs:comment A specialization of #$Animal and an instance of
            #$OrganismClassificationType.  Each instance of #$Homeotherm
            is a  warm-blooded  animal.  That is, each instance is an
            animal that is able to maintain a stable body temperature
            relative to its environmental temperature. Cf. #$Poikilotherm.

:PumpingGasEvent rdfs:comment The collection of events in which a discrete
            portion of gasoline is pumped *entirely* see
            #$FluidFlow-Translation vs #$Translation-Complete from a
            pump into the gas tank of a vehicle.  Every complete
            #$PumpingGasEvent has a #$subEvents in which #$PumpingFluid
            is occurring.  Also, every #$PumpingGasEvent has a number of
            sub-events in which a portion of gas is completely
            transmitted into a gas tank see #$Translation-Complete.

:BiologicalSubspecies rdfs:comment A specialization of #$BiologicalTaxon whose
            instances are more restrictive  than those of
            #$BiologicalSpecies.  Each instance of
            #$BiologicalSubspecies  is a specialization of some instance
            of #$BiologicalSpecies.  Members of  different subspecies of
            the same species can produce fertile offspring by
            interbreeding; but such offspring are not members of either
            of the parental  subspecies, although they are members of
            the common species.  All instances  of a given biological
            subspecies have significant traits or collections of  traits
            in common that are not shared by all other members of the
            subsuming  species.    A #$BiologicalSubspecies is formed by
            inbreeding of a restricted group of  members of the same
            species.  This can happen naturally through geographic
            isolation or intentionally through controlled reproduction
            to create, for  example, dog breeds or crop strains.

:isTheAttributeOfSomethingConsistingOf rdfs:comment isTheAttributeOfSomethingConsistingOf relates a
     type of AttributeValue to some instance of SubstanceType,
     asserting that the Object or Substance thus characterized 
     has the Substance in object position as main constituent for an Object
     or has dominant component susbtance for a Substance..
     
     This is a very specialized relation, used to create a direct link
     from certain attributes such as Wooden to the substance
     Wood - this is used for attributes that reflect substance composition.
     
     When a PhysicalObject is related by these relations:
        ?Obj hasAttributeValue ?Att and
        ?Att isTheAttributeOfSomethingConsistingOf ?Subst
      that is equivalent to asserting:
         ?Obj consistsMostlyOfSubstance ?Subst
         
     When a PhysicalSubsatnce is related by this relation:
        ?Subst1 isTheAttributeOfSomethingConsistingOf ?Subst2 
      that is equivalent to asserting:
         ?Subst1 hasMainComponentSubstance ?Subst2
         
     This relation is therefore redundant, except to express the meaning of
       words in English and other languages such as wooden or woolen
       that attribute composition to objects or substances, suitable for
       implementation in OWL.  For an FOL version, this relation may be
       superseded by rules that achieve the same effect without redundancy.
       @ToDo: review for FOL version.

:Radian rdfs:comment SI plane angle measure.  Symbol: rad.  It is the angle of a circle 
    subtended by an arc equal in length to the circles radius.
    Another definition is:  the plane angle between two radii of a circle 
    which cut off on the circumference an arc equal in length to the radius.
    Radian = m/m = 1.

          some mixture of liquid and solid substances perhaps dissolved
          becomes more Viscous by any of several processes intentional or natural,
          such asConcentratingaSolution usually by evaporation, but potentially 
          by freezing out the solvent.or adding materials e.g. flour 
          to dissolve and increase viscosity, or by heating or some chemical
          process,
            Includes  transitive and intransitive senses of thicken
        
           The restriction refers to FodThickener but a Thickening
             may occur in substances other than foods, and by processes other than
             adding thickeners.

           Includes all threee verb senses of thicken in WordNet:
             1. 2 thicken, inspissate - make thick or thicker; 
                Thicken the sauce; inspissate the tar so that it becomes pitch
	     2. 2 thicken, inspissate - become thick or thicker; The sauce thickened;
	        The egg yolk will inspissate"
             3. thicken, inspissate - make viscous or dense; thicken the sauce by adding flour

:Hurrah rdfs:comment The word hurrah suddenly emitted  loudly, to express approval or
       agreement, or elation at an accomplishment.

        WN verb hurrah:

:Cow-FemaleHerdAnimal rdfs:comment The collection of female herd animals that can be
            referred to as #$Cows, such as #$Elephants, Buffalo, etc.
            The contrast term is #$Bull - thus, a cow X usually implies
            the existence of #$Bull X e.g., there are #$Cow #$Elephants
            and #$Bull #$Elephants. See also #$Bull-MaleHerdAnimal.

:EatingUtensil rdfs:comment A FoodUtensil used directly in the act of eating food -
          knife, fork, spoon.
        
        Cyc: SilverwarePiece Not necessarily silver - eating implements like
            knife, fork, spoon.  These are not #$GraspingImplements.

:ConcaveObject rdfs:comment COSMO note: this is an Object or part of an Object
           that is concave, not the attribute of being concavce.
           
           InCyc called simply Concave.
           Cyc: An attribute of a surface meaning that it is
            bumped or indented inward.  A concave surface has a pair of
            points which are both closer to a viewer than points on the
            surface between them.   Depending on the context, it may
            have relatively small subregions which have convexities
            e.g. wrinkles, small dents, corrugations or are flat so
            long as the overall shape is concave.  Saddle-shapes,
            although convex in certain dimensions, are concave in others
            and are therefore concave.

:Parasite rdfs:comment Corresponds to noun sense 1 of parasite in WordNet:
          1. 4 parasite - an animal or plant that lives in or on a host

         .

           is performed in a hurried or rushed manner.  The words associated with
           this sense are often used with the meaning of the process of
           going, rather than the completed movement; the distinction must
           be made by the Lexical Expert.

             sense 1 of race; it is also part of sense 4 of rush,

               step on it; He rushed down the hall to receive his guests;

           WN hurry
            1. 30 travel rapidly, speed, hurry, zip - move very fast; 
               The runner zipped past us at breakneck speed

:Fetus rdfs:comment CYC: A specialization of #$AnimalBodyPart and
            #$SolidTangibleThing, and an instance of
            #$UniqueAnatomicalPartType. Each instance of this collection
            is a #$BiologicalLivingObject resident in a pregnant
            #$Mammal which, after the separation of the #$AmnioticSac,
            will develop into a mammalian baby.  By contrast, the term
            #$Embryo means all tissue that has decended from the
            fertilized #$Ovum, including the fetal part of the

            the #$UmbilicalCord, as well as the #$Fetus. Thus note that
            a #$Fetus is an #$AnimalBodyPart not because it is a
            body-part of its mother, but because it is a body-part of
            its #$Embryo.

              1. fetus, foetus - an unborn or unhatched vertebrate in the later stages 
               of development showing the main recognizable features of the mature animal

:Meninges rdfs:comment The collection of all meninges, of which there are

            #$CentralNervousSystem.  The three #$Meninges lie within the
            #$Skull for that portion which covers the #$Brain and
            consist of the #$DuraMater on the outside, the
            #$ArachnoidMater in the middle and the #$PiaMater coating

            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of meninges in Wordnet:

            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of seam in WordNet:

          unions that are recognized as marriage by law.

             1. 17 married - - joined in matrimony; a married man; a married couple
           WN adjective united:

            that uses geneteic material only from a single parent.

            organisms and viruses.
           
            corresponds to part of sense 1 the asexual part of reproduction in WordNet;

:causedTheStoppingOf rdfs:comment causedTheStoppingOf relates an Event or EventType ?E1
     to another Event or EventType ?E2 that is caused to stop by ?E1.

       understanding that what is stopped is the *functioning* of the Device.

     stop itself when the stopped Event has ceased; a noise that

:TypicalAdultPerson rdfs:comment The Type of all adult humans whose characteristics fall into

        NOTE: *** concerning the weight of a typical adult: ***
        from: http://www3.lehigh.edu/News/V2news_story.asp?iNewsID=1765
        ** Even the crash test dummies are putting on weight.**
	   As Americans get heavier, the people who build and regulate cars,
	boats and planes are trying to keep up, adjusting design standards and 
	safety rules to account for newly recognized safety risks posed by those 
	extra pounds per person.
	    The Coast Guard this week set a new standard for calculating how many
	passengers a vessel can bear. The Federal Aviation Administration is making
	similar changes for airplanes. Automakers are increasingly using plus-size 
	dummies to test their seat belts and air bags.
           According to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
        a solid majority of Americans, 65 percent, are overweight. The average American 
        man grew from 166 pounds in 1960 to 191 pounds in 2002, while the average womans
        weight rose from 140 to 164 pounds.
            These overweight and obese people can affect other people, said Shin-Yi Chou,
	a professor at Lehigh University who studies the economics of obesity.
	When you increase the weight aboard airplanes, for example, there is an increased risk.
	We probably need government intervention.
            Last month, the National Transportation Safety Board concluded that an outdated 
         passenger weight formula was partly to blame when a water shuttle in Baltimore Harbor
         capsized in March 2004, killing five people.
             The Lady D set out with 25 people aboard, the maximum allowed by Coast Guard
         rules based on a 40-year-old estimate that the average person weighs 140 pounds.
         In fact, the people aboard averaged 168 pounds. The boat overturned when winds 
         gusted suddenly.

          as subtypes physical Obstacle and barriers such as walls, but can include abstract
          hindrances such as lack of money, lack of permission, some insurmountable physical
          property, or intractable opposition e.g. a wall of opposition.  Thus the barrier may
          be literal or metaphorical.

:Account rdfs:comment COSMO: Account is a broad category including 
         Bank accounts, insurance accounts, stock broker accounts, and in general any
         legal agrement between two or more parties regarding the
         handling of money or some fungible equivalent, which may
         exist or come into existence based on some contingency as
         with an insurance account.  An organization or part of 
         an Organization may also maintain an account for
         another group or part of the same organization.  In some
         cases, money is simply held by one party to be disbursed at
         the direction of another party, and that agreement is also
         an Account.  Since money or its fungible equivalent can be
         withdrawn from an Account, it is a subclass of Source - i.e.
         it is a source of Money.  Each Account is a MoneyObject, and has
         some value in some currency at any given time.  Insurance
         accounts present a special nuance: if they depend on a contingency
         such as death, their value while the subject is alive is zero, but if the subject
         dies, their value goes up to the value of the policy.
         
         Because Account is a high-level category in some taxonomies, it
         is superfluously directly connected to owl:Thing for easy discovery by those
         familiar with such classifications.
         
         The monetary value of an Account is related by the hasMonetaryValue relation.
           @ToDo: is this the same as account balance??
         
         Cyc:  An instance of #$ObjectType and a specialization
            of #$LegalAgreement. Each instance of #$Account is a
            recorded obligation of some particular type between
            specified parties, consisting of  funds  not necessarily
            monetary funds which typically can be added to and drawn
            upon. Positive examples include instances of
            #$RetirementAccount, #$TravelExpenseAccount, and of the many
            types of #$FinancialAccount. Note that the contents of an
            account need not be monetary; for example, the contents may
            be amounts of time, as in the specializations
            #$VacationAccount and #$SickLeaveAccount. #$Account does not
            include debt obligations of fixed face value that cannot be
            increased or reduced such as instances of #$Bond-Agreement.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of account in WordNet:
             1. 564 account, business relationship - a formal contractual relationship
               established to provide for regular banking or brokerage or business services;
               he asked to see the executive who handled his account

:Talking rdfs:comment A collection of actions. Each instance of

            sometimes people can talk using some non-oral language,
            e.g., #$AmericanSignLanguage.  #$Talking, however, is

:Rather rdfs:comment Rather is an AdverbialModifier that can modify
          QualitativeAttributeValues to create new QualitativeAttributeValues, 
           of the same qualitative type as the base value, but at a level of definiteness or emphasis

           Somewhat, and for distinctly more than the average, use Very.

           the attribute it modifies *definitely* applies to the thing that the
           attribute modifies, and the degree of intensity of the attribute
           is more than somewhat and less than very.  If a person is *rather* tall, 
           then the speaker thinks that s/he is unquestionably tall. 
           When the attributes are context sensitive the
           modifier is also context sensitive, so it is an instance of LogicalFunctionType.
           This sense is used as a modifier of AttributeValues, which show up linguistically
           as adjectives or sometimes as adverbs.
                Shes doing rather well His handwriting is rather poor
           
           Corresponds to sense 1 of rather in RHW:
              1. in a measure; to a certain extent; somewhat: rather good.
           
           Corresponds approximately to adverb sense 2 of rather in WordNet,
           but the sense sort of, implying some question as to the applicability of the
           attribute modified by rather is *not* included in this type.  When this
           AdverbialModifier is applied to an attribute, there is no question that
           the speaker thinks that the attribute is appropriate to the thing it modifies.
            2. 54 rather, kind of, kinda, sort of - to some great or small extent;
              it was rather cold; the party was rather nice; the knife is rather dull;

:Typical rdfs:comment The FunctionalAttribute Typical, when modifying some
        type, is a function that creates a subtype of the type modified,
        and all instances of that subtype have one or more properties that
        are held by *most* of the members of that type.  A Typical instance of a class
        is also a prototypical instance.
        
        This is an intensive subtype of Common in eaning thatin this
          context some type of thing the thing described occurs so often
          that is it the most often observed of all the possibiities.

        See also logical function TheTypical that can generate a typical instance of
        a type in an FOL implementation.
        
        Deciding what properties to select to interpret something as typical of its type 
        can vary from one person to another.  The properties that make
        a thing typical will be specified within the meaning of this 
        fuction, and will vary with the type being modified.  Thus this
        function may be very complex in its implementation.  One possible
        means of simplifying this function is to keep the list of
        properties that are considered in deciding typicality as part 
        of the description of the type itself.
        
        Typicality will be a function of the type, and will not constrain
        the typicality of subtypes.  Thus the type Typical Person will
        contain many instances that are not present in the type Typical Infant,
        and Typcial Infant will contain instances not present in
        Typical PrematureBaby.
        
        In practice, the values of the attributes that are decisive
        in determnining typicality may be ranges of values rather than
        individual values, such as the height of a typical person.
        
        This method of interpreting the meaning of modification of
        nouns by adjectives has not yet v0.48 been implemented in 
        a Language Understanding program.

       Includes senses 1 and 3 of adjective typical in Wordnet:        
         1. 27 typical - exhibiting the qualities or characteristics that
                 identify a group or kind or category; a typical American girl;
                 a typical suburban community; the typical car owner drives 
                 10,000 miles a year; a painting typical of the Impressionist school;

             typical teenage behavior

:Probability rdfs:comment A Probability is a DimensionlessRatio 
         which is a measure of the number of times a certain
         situation will occur divided by the total number of times
         a more general situation is observed.  This measure may be
         derived by historical observation and projection of historical
         trends to the future, or by calculation from
         component elements of the relevant situation type.
         Probabilities can be used for various situations, such as
         the probability that something is true now; the probability that
         something will become true; the probability that some
         event will have a particular outcome, and others.  An instance
         of Probability can be represented as a limit, such as GreaterThanHalf;
         see Likely
         
         COSMO note: in COSMO, a Probability may be represented as a number
         or range, which would be an instance of Probability, but may also be
         represented by a VerbalProbability, which is a class that represents a
         range of values in the range of 0 to 1.  The use of a VerbalProbability
         allows closer alignment with linguistic usage, and also permits
         subclassing of values.  The hasProbability relation can use either
         a numerical instance of Probability or a subclass of VerbalProbability
         as its value.
         
         Cyc: A specialization of #$Quantity q.v.. Each
            #$Probability is a degree or range of likelihoods that
            can be attributed to a statement with respect to the
            likelihood of its being or becoming true.  Although not
            #$MeasurableQuantityies q.v. in the full sense of that
            term, probabilities are often characterized and compared
            numerically, along a scale from 0 to 1.  #$ProbabilityFn 0
            is icertain falsity/i and #$ProbabilityFn
            1 is icertain truth/i.  See also
            #$ProbabilityInterval, the collection of all real number
            intervals between 0 and 1 inclusive, and thus of all
            possible arguments for #$ProbabilityFn.

         The plural form chances is also used in essentially the same
            sense. e.g.: What are the chances that a meteor will fall in the yard? -
            same as What is the probability that a meteor will fall in the yard?
            The difference may be only one of formality.  The form chances 
            may suggest an answer in the form of a ratio - odds, such as
            1 in a million.
                        
         Corresponds to noun sense 1 of probability and noun sense 4
             of chance and sense 1 of likelihood and sense 1 of odds  in WordNet:
           WN chance:
             4. 2 probability, chance - a measure of how likely it is that
                some event will occur; a number expressing the ratio of favorable 
                cases to the whole number of cases possible; the probability that 
                an unbiased coin will fall with the head up is 0.5
           WN noun likelihood:
             1. 2 likelihood, likeliness - the probability of a specified outcome
           WN noun odds:
